The main outcomes of this project include:

1. Enabled the PI and his students to publish over 50 peer-reviewed research articles during the project period in Nature Climate Change, Nature Communications, J. Climate, Climate Dynamics, Climatic Change, Geophys. Res. Lett., and other journals on the role of natural variability and human influence in the observed changes in precipitation and drought over many regions;

2. Helped train two PhD students and one Master's student, and a postdoc researcher;

3. Key scientifc findings include:

a. Drought and precipitation changes so far over most regions are still dominated by natural varaibility, with anthoropogenic signal being detectable only for the global mean;

b. The Inter-decadal Pacifc Oscillation (IPO) has major influences on temeprature and precipitation over many land regions such as Southwest North America, Eastern Australia, and Southern Africa, and it often causes apperant trends in the regional T and P over these regions over a period of multi-decades;

c. The IPO can also modulate ENSO's climatic influence over eastern Australia and other regions, causing some decades to have stronger ENSO influences than in other decades;

d. The Atlantic Multid-decadal Oscillation (AMO) since 1950 may be partially forced by anthropogenic and volcanic aerosols, and the AMO is behind a decadal seesaw pattern between JJA Sahel rainfall and Southeast Amazon rainfall;

e. In contrast, the IPO since 1920 results largely from internal variaiblity, also volcanic forcing and anthoropogenic aerosols may have contribute its variations significantly since the early 1990s.



